  <span id="freeText12801273062572561249" style="display:none">It’s a beautiful story of a co-dependent, toxic relationship between a writer and her hired help where a weird power struggle never seems to end. Emerence, the said help, seems to be more in charge than her supposed employers. She is despotic, mysterious and strong-willed. Her employer, the writer and the narrator of this (maybe semi-autobiographical) book seems emotionally volatile which makes her susceptible to Emerence’s moods and tantrums. Emerence is not a demure servant, she comes and goes as she pleases but sometimes she works all night, cleaning everything in sight. When the writer adopts a dog, Emerence becomes its true master, which adds more fuel to their existing jealousy. Emerence never stops being tyrannical, even in her expressions of love.<br /><br />In the very beginning the narrator tells us Emerence is dead and the she killed her. We suspect this might be a hyperbole but we are still along for the ride all the way to the heart-breaking end, slightly amazed that the narrator hints it’s the author herself talking and at the same paints such an unflattering picture of herself. I got the feeling the book was written as a form of apology and penance. As if through writing about Emerence, the narrator could finally get to know here the way she couldn’t while Emerence was still alive. Emerence is elevated here, to a semi-mythical figure, the type of ‘salt of the earth’ kind of character that most writers for some reason believe are more authentic in their existence than the intellectual (don’t get me started on that trope, though). <br />Additionally, we can also interpret the entire thing as a metaphor of the oppressive communist regime, which is also a rule for any book written during an oppressive communist regime. They are always somehow about that too. <br /><br />I would recommend this book for fans of Ferrante. It’s like Ferrante but with a gloomy Eastern European sheen and none of the Southern flair.<br /> <br /><br /></span>
